I call utter bullshit on this. It’s straight-up illegal to do that anywhere in Europe, and in many US states, and American hotels don’t plant security cameras in non-public spaces as a matter of professional course. They know you steal or trash a room when they notice the stuff missing or the detritus left behind, not because they’re fucking filming you doing it.

Whatever OP’s picture is, I will bet money it’s not a hotel.

You can visit all year around, but each region has its "

column10:
season.
The desert parts of Kazakhstan, Uzbekistan and the whole of Turkmenistan are best visited in spring and autumn because it can get hot in summer, easily more than 40°C for days, although dry heat, so more bearable than similar humid destinations.
The mountain parts of Kazakhstan, Kyrgyzstan and Tajikistan have their main season in summer when you can hike everywhere and all the summer facilities are open. In winter there are fewer places where you can go skiing and winter hiking, but in early spring and late autumn you'
column12:

My russian is very very basic, will I survive?
Little Russian is already better than no Russian.
Learn some useful common phrases (e.g. Pimsleur Russian) and download an offline translator. Make sure that you have a Russian keyboard enabled in case somebody wants to translate to English.
I personally make sure to write down any amounts negotiated (especially taxi fares) on paper or on my phone and show them to prevent and misunderstandings or "

column28:
Samarkand before crossing the border to Panjakent (TJ), going down to Dushanbe, the base for planning any activities in the GBAO.
The return from Dushanbe would be via Khujand to Tashkent, if you don'
column29:
t want to do the Anzob twice, you can also go via Termez, possible even by train.
From Tashkent you can either go North to see more desert/steppe in Kazakhstan or East to the Fergana valley, ending up in Osh (KG).
From there you can do the 10-hour ride to Bishkek, stopping over in Toktogul for a night if you want.
In Northern Kyrgyzstan, you will very likely spend some time in Issyk-Kul, both on the lake and the surrounding mountains, stopping over in Karakol before heading towards Almaty, easily reached via Bishkek, the more adventurous and scenic path via the Karakara valley.
From Almaty you can go West to Taraz/Shymkent/Turkestan for the Silk Road sights or North to Karaganda and Astana (not much to see but surprisingly cool during summer due it being very windy).

Obviously this is a very packed itinerary for a two-months, so you want to drop destinations and flesh out your stay at others.
You can do 4 out of 5 countries in less than 24 hours (by bus and taxi between Khujand TJ and Bishkek KG), but that'

Like mountains? Then you'

column38:
and smaller destinations like the countless fortresses in the desert.

All countries but Turkmenistan give you ample time to visit and visa runs can be had for cheap.

It is really easy to go country collecting (my passport has pages and pages filled with entry and exit stamps due to extended weekend trips), but in the end you do not want to rush from one place to the next because of a tight itinerary.
Yes, you can visit Khiva/Bukhara in one day, but strolling through town in the late evening or early morning with nobody else in sight is something you can only do if you spend a night or two there.
The same can be said about chilling on the shores of Issyk-Kul or spending a lazy day in a yurt camp reading a book while listening to nature.

Anyway, let me know if you want to know more about a place.', 'filename': 'KZ_Baiterek', 'ext': '.jpg', 'w': 800, 'h': 519, 'tn_w': 125, 'tn_h': 81, 'tim': 1670479737111043, 'time': 1670479737, 'md5': 'OcYsL0V5silRRIxiBYLItg==', 'fsize': 65921, 'resto': 2366410}, {'no': 2369796, 'now': '12/08/22(Thu)02:18:07', 'name': 'Anonymous', 'com': '>

column5:

Condesa, Roma, Hippodrome: safe, full of expats, everyone also speaks English, great food, great parks, no scary stuff, lots of bars and night life and cafes.

Centro Histórico: historical, as you said, but gets kind of dead at night. You will likely be taking an Uber to Roma/Condesa to go out to dinner/drinks anyway. Better hotels for short term stays and beautiful buildings

Tepito: what people claim is the most sketchy/dangerous

Del Carmen: slightly less City/night life and more local, probably more “””authentic””” if you’re a dumbass faggot who measures trips by how unejoyable they are.

Polanco: the Hudson Yards of CDMX, where it is exceptionally rich and safe but not enjoyable to be there at all because it’s just middle aged millionaires driving around to boutiques.

Do yourself a favor OP and do what everyone ever suggests, and stay in Roma Norte, Roma Sur, Condesa, or Hippodrome. There’s a reason these are the most commonly suggested neighborhoods without fail and have been for years and will be probably forever.', 'time': 1670612055, 'resto': 2369738}, {'no': 2370510, 'now': '12/09/22(Fri)16:45:06', 'name': 'Anonymous', 'com': '>

column5:

Final notes.
Circled in red are are arm rests, once everyone is seated, you may pull yours down.
(1) if you get to your seat before the window seat person arrives , and you have an Aisle seat, you MUST stand up and get in the walkway for him to sit down, there is not room for him or her to sit otherwise.
(1)during take off and landing they will force you to wear a seatbelt, if you can’t find your seatbelt, relax, take a breath, and look under the edges and back of your seat, the seatbelt straps have fallen down to the sides.
(1) During most of the flight you need to keep your carry on bag stored. There is overhead compartments you can put them in or under the seat in front of you (most cases).
New flyers sometimes think planes are like trains, and try to drag wayy too many creature comforts onto a plane, you only need one small bag, with som reading material or laptop, music device with headphones.
(1) forgot to say, at security if you have a laptop they will sometimes. make you turn it on usually to check that it is real, it needs to go through security x-ray in its own box, not with your carry on.', 'filename': '7B709B31-442E-4498-AE4B-6AFB9CF77D3D', 'ext': '.jpg', 'w': 1600, 'h': 800, 'tn_w': 125, 'tn_h': 62, 'tim': 1670566430328396, 'time': 1670566430, 'md5': '0T9DxUbaxLHYEbk11tEH2A==', 'fsize': 114721, 'resto': 2370190}, {'no': 2370342, 'now': '12/09/22(Fri)06:08:36', 'name': 'Anonymous', 'com': '>

It'
column7: s hands down the most beautiful city I&#039
column8: ve been to in my entire life. Table Mountain is a crazy scenic backdrop for urban life, and there&#039
column9:
s a beach with great surfing about 20-30 minutes away from the downtown area (CBD).

I highly recommend driving out to Kirstenbosch (sp). It'
column10: s one of the nicest parks I&#039
column11:
ve been to. Beautiful garden with a mountain looming over it. I felt like I was in Eden.

Income inequality is insane there, though. The nice areas are really nice but the dangerous areas are super fucking dangerous and you should not fuck around because you will end up in a dangerous situation. When I was there a lady got kidnapped in broad daylight. Thugs pulled her out of her sports car and blocked her in (https://www.iol.co.za/news/south-africa/western-cape/watch-woman-kidnapped-in-broad-daylight-in-cape-town-from-her-yellow-audi-r8-0ee47c81-be7b-4d69-a363-79415c2f03e8)

I had a great time and would definitely live there if I could. I stayed in the Cartwright Building on Adderley Street and had top floor panoramic views of the city for about $70 USD a night.

Racial tensions are still pretty high there. I talked to a lot of people and got the feeling that there was an uneasy peace between all the races. I never encountered any racism from anyone and overall the people there were pretty friendly and fun to be around.

Also, the Garden Route is a beautiful drive that rivals Big Sur, California.

I took a train up to MTL with a bunch of friends for the weekend to celebrate my eighteenth birthday (drinking age was 18 at the time, I think it may be 19 now?).

But it’s also a big, world-class major city. And the fact that it’s almost aggressively Francophone gives it some cultural appeal for Anglo yanks—it seems a lot more foreign to an American than (other) Canadian cities, but you don’t have to fly there.

I also like that my terrible attempts at French have always been received with very good cheer. column3:
2370372
>
column4:
How much does language learning improve your experience of traveling, working, and living abroad?
Working and living abroad, immeasurably. Even if you’re in a working environment that uses your language, you’re guaranteed to get far more out of life when you can talk to locals in their native tongue. Traveling, it’s maybe less essential, but it certainly never makes an experience worse, only better (with a tiny number of exceptions—because speaking a language always makes you harder to rip off or scam, some locals who might have liked to scam you might regard foreigners speaking their language with some suspicion or even hostility. But it’s a vanishingly small number of such cases.)

>
column5:
Could it be said to be the key to having a good experience?
It has always enriched my experiences when I’ve been able to speak with locals in their own languages. But I know lots of people who can’t or don’t learn languages who’ve had good experiences as well. And for a minority of travelers or expats, the illusion-dispelling nature of speaking a local language might be a mixed bag. People don’t always like what they hear once they actually understand it all.', 'time': 1670594529, 'resto': 2370372}, {'no': 2370389, 'now': '12/09/22(Fri)09:32:33', 'name': 'Anonymous', 'com': '>

68,2368523,,,12/06/22(Tue)01:04:22,Anonymous,"It’s been many years since I’ve posted on /trv/
I’m an old anon. Been married for 10 years and got divorced recently.
While married I couldn’t travel.
When I was young, from 15 to 30 I travelled a lot, many of the countries I visited I am told are not the same at all anymore.
(Myanmar when it first opened to the west, Cambodia before 2000, China and Vietnam before they modernised. Been all through where the war in Ukraine is, some far flung parts of Russia.)
The countries I miss are not the same anymore, a lot was before even mobile phones let alone apps were around.

Basically I’m looking for not just places but ways of travel that suits my age. I want to start it again, but aren’t interested in being the oldest guy at a full moon party or cooming my way around seedy third world brothels (are they even a thing anymore or does pussy have an Uber eats like app)

My circle of friends who are all married with kids, some even have grandkids, either are the types who go on cruises pretty much for the free food, or are the types that go holidaying with business associates.
Both of these are not really my thing. I’d most likely be travelling alone, I’m ok with learning languages.

column4:

column5:
what level of sussing you out do they even do for domestic flights?
You pass through security, hand luggage, wallet, phone, laptop etc will go into a plastic bucket and through the x-ray. You walk through a metal detector. You may get called aside to have the metal detector wand waved over you, sometimes a pat down, but that is rare. A security pajeet may approach you and ask to swab your hands and bag for residue, this takes a minute. Once that is done then you are airside and can wait at the boarding gate, there is usually no further security. At the boarding gate some airlines (namely Jetstar) can be pedantic about measuring the dimensions of your hand luggage and weighing it. If it is a little over they will want you to check it in and they will probably charge you for that.', 'time': 1670235623, 'resto': 2366333}, {'no': 2368105, 'now': '12/05/22(Mon)06:39:10', 'name': 'Anonymous', 'com': '>

column26:

Brought my cat from the US to EU with me and then he’s coming to Japan with me eventually. You gotta get some forms filled out and authorized by USDA APHIS (google eu pet health certificate).
I assume it’s similar for the reverse. Check out the APHIS website.
Go through the steps and you’ll be able to bring him. I’m glad I brought mine. Some airlines like Delta let you bring them in cabin but they have quotas per flight so you’ll have to book the flight and then call in. Or vice versa. I think it was $200 international to bring him with me on Delta. There are companies that make specific airline regulated pet carriers made to fit under the seat in front of you. I wouldn’t do cargo, especially for long flights, animals have and do die down there. The airlines claim it’s safe but it still happens, also imagine being locked in a dark weirdly pressurized area with all kinds of unfamiliar loud noises. I don’t think my cat would enjoy it nor would I risk his life to save a couple hundred dollars.
Japan requires their own specific form and I had to have rabies testing done 6 months in advance. Not sure if the US will require this, but you will definitely have to have him up to date on rabies vaccinations. The certificate process is basically just endorse/prove that your pet is 100% rabies free.
I won’t lie it’s a lot harder traveling with a pet, you have to make sure they’re cozy every place you move but if you’re just coming to the US and staying in one place it isn’t bad. But there are times I wish I didn’t bring mine as it’s hard to just fuck off for weeks or take trains between countries, things like that. I guess you won’t have to worry about trains much in burger land, but just be aware it is kind of a pain at times. But overall worth having my lil homie with me, especially now during the holidays that I’m spending all alone away from family.', 'time': 1670531849, 'resto': 2369513}]",1670531849,0.0,0.0,11.0,2.0,,

I drove across Zimbabwe in 2018 (Mutare to Vic Falls). Don'
column11: t listen to what the other anons are saying, it&#039
column12: s not actually that bad if you keep your wits about you and you&#039
column13:
re not a total retard.

To be fair, Harare is a shithole. If you visit, definitely do not stay in the city center. Generally the northeastern suburbs are the nicest and you should look for a hotel/airbnb there. Barring that, you can stay in Belvedere to the west of the city, which is where I stayed and is somewhat cheaper. It'
column14:
s a largely Indian and Chinese community. The Harare Gardens are also beautiful and worth strolling around (during the day of course).

Bulawayo might be a better city for Rhodesia nostalgia (it was Zim'
column15: s biggest city until the 30s). Bulawayo is generally quite a pleasant town and you can see a lot of Rhodesian heritage just walking around. You can visit the railway museum which is for spergs but it&#039
column16: s still kind of cool to see the old Rhodesian locomotives. I also stopped for a drink at the &quot
column17: Cape to Cairo&quot
column18: Bar on Mugabe Street which has sort of a &quot
column20:
theme and does jazz music at night.

About an hour'
column21: s drive from Bulawayo, visit Matobo National Park to see Cecil Rhodes&#039
column24:
s lots of other stuff to do in the park as well).

If you'
column25: re at all interested in African history you can also visit Great Zimbabwe (~4h east of Bulawayo), which is supposedly one of the greatest &quot
column26: castles&quot
column27:
built in pre-colonial Africa.

Lastly, I would recommend taking the train from Bulawayo to Vic Falls. They still operate old Rhodesian Railways rolling stock from the 1950s and 60s. It'
column28: s an overnight trip where you basically wake up in Vic Falls. Booking a sleeper car is super cheap--but when I was there it had to be done at the train station in cash. Idk if they&#039
column29:
ve fixed this by now.

As usual, be cautious with your belongings. All the answers ITT are correct.
FB/IG/etc really corrupted the motivations people have for travel these days compared to 20+ years ago where you had to be strongly interested to visit somewhere.
Smartphones spread English language and appalling American culture to every far flung corner of the globe to a point I have seen locals in Rwanda, to Tasmania, to Buryat, to Cambodia who are trying to become professional rappers. This garbage simply didn’t exist decades ago.
A large majority of the world has been seduced and sold the lemon that is American culture.

On cooming, when old fags say Thailand is dead- it is.
Modern Thailand is like what McDonalds is for burgers, to pussy.
Philippines, Thailand, Cambodia, before smart phones you’d meet a girl who was truly innocent on some levels, who barely spoke English, who’d meet you in a bar &
column7:
be enamoured by you. You would take her with you as you travel the country, she’d clean and cook for you and negotiate dealings with locals without any predatory aspects of SEA today. I’m not romanticising it, it was like you were the best thing that ever walked into her life.
The sex was endless so old fags stayed to the one girl not the fuck anything that moves approach like now. It was like that once in a lifetime type of fling. The girls would have friends and even organise 5sums etc for you on a special occasion (once they knew they had you) as long as you took care of her friends and were serious about them.
This is why so many men now in their 60-80’s who went to Thailand married the girls. They werent marrying crazy bar girls but the best most unique &

This concept is now laughable in Thailand.
It’s all been completely turned inside out to being unrecognisable.

column16:
How easy was it to get there and back?
As far as I can tel, the only way to get to Greenland is via either Keflavik, Iceland (Reykjavik'
column17: s airport), or Copenhagen via Air Greenland&#039
column18:
s A330 passenger jet.
I did see one plane with a with a Canadian livery, so presumably they fly to Kangerlussuaq from somewhere in Nunavut.
>
column19:
What about getting around?
Public transit (ie busses) only exist in Nuuk it seems. Walking, biking, snowmachining, 4 wheelers, and cars are the primary forms of travel. Nuuk also had taxis, and Kangerlussuaq had a shuttle operating between the airport and town center.
>
column20:
Was it easy to book a place to stay?
My experience might be unique, but the my hotel'

column22: t working and I was forced to call and email with the hotel&#039
column23:
s front desk. The 2 or 3 other hotels seemed to operate the same. So, not terrible, but not ideal.
>
column24:
How was the internet and did you shitpost on a 4chan board with flags?
Internet was exceptional. Wifi in my room hovered around the 100-200mb mark for down, and like 75 for up. Genuinely impressed with the internet and cell service infrastructure they have there. Our Danish friends must be helping out. And yes, I did. Every niche place I go I always make time to post from >

Even for me as a SWE most companies won’t even interview me while abroad even though I still have a US address. Most of them just say to contact them when I’m home in the states. The only way it seems to work well is if you do it for shorter periods of time, and are already employed at a company that doesn’t care.

I don’t know if you’re schizophrenic, but it’s definitely something that does and will actually happen—the two biggest firms where I live have employees from 70+ countries.

column15: why the fuck would a company go through the hassle of interviewing someone that they know doesn&#039
column16:
t yet have the necessary permits to work in the country, and then spend the time facilitating the acquisition of said permits and accommodation etc.?
For big companies this is no problem—my wife’s firm actually has leverage with the immigration authorities that makes issuing permits quick and easy. And the firm mostly imports and exports people as internal transfers—someone who already knows the business and brings perspectives or skills from a different market is well worth importing. Our relo package (international movers, temporary housing on arrival, security deposit at new permanent apartment, many other perks) was worth a couple hundred grand and included a work permit for me, who wasn’t even being hired by the company.', 'time': 1670445555, 'resto': 2369464}]",1670445555,0.0,0.0,,,is working abroad actually a real thing i feel like i'
